			<h4><a id="comment_link_64358606" name="comment_link_64358606" href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23274788&amp;cid=64358606" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64358606)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64358606" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64358606); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Firethorn">Firethorn</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Firethorn">( 177587 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64358606"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64358606"><p>1.  I'd say around 2015 or so, you started seeing EPA mileage ratings being higher for automatics than manuals.  This was around the time that automatics started having more gears than manuals - IE the manual has 5 forward, the automatic might have 8.<br>2.  They generally handle uphill/downhill just fine.</p><p>I'll note that I don't have much experience with traditional automatics - I moved from a manual transmission to a hybrid with a CVT.  The motor can patch over a lot of acceleration hesitation from the engine.</p></div>
	</div>

